<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,310,1882,1908]" box="[189,310,1882,1908]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1882,1908]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1882,1908]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1399,1929,2027]" lastBlockId="8.[189,1399,267,510]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Body with slightly oval or pear-shaped prosoma and elongated narrow abdomen. A pair of tear-shaped spots on the area of fovea (sometimes poorly visible in dark-coloured specimens) is also characteristic (
<bibRefCitation author="Wesolowska W. &amp; Russell-Smith A." box="[197,628,2001,2027]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="553 - 619" refId="ref8594" refString="Wesolowska W. &amp; Russell-Smith A. 2011. Jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae) from southern Nigeria. Annales Zoologici 61: 553 - 619. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 000345411 x 603409" type="journal article" year="2011">Wesołowska &amp; Russell-Smith 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wesolowska W. &amp; Haddad C. R." box="[643,1000,2001,2027]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="177 - 240" refId="ref8548" refString="Wesolowska W. &amp; Haddad C. R. 2013. New data on the jumping spiders of South Africa (Araneae: Salticidae). African Invertebrates 54: 177 - 240. https: // doi. org / 10.5733 / afin. 054.0111" type="journal article" year="2013">Wesołowska &amp; Haddad 2013</bibRefCitation>
). In most species, abdomen with contrasting pattern of transverse bands or median light band. Chelicerae unidentate. First two pairs of legs substantially stouter and longer than the rest, with numerous spines. Bulbus generally rounded and oval in some species (
<bibRefCitation author="Wesolowska W. &amp; Edwards G. B." box="[523,900,339,365]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="733 - 772" refId="ref8501" refString="Wesolowska W. &amp; Edwards G. B. 2012. Jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae) of the Calabar area (SE Nigeria). Annales Zoologici 62: 733 - 772. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 000345412 x 659786" type="journal article" year="2012">Wesołowska &amp; Edwards 2012</bibRefCitation>
), characterized by small, triangular flap. Thin and long embolus encircling bulbus partially or fully. Palpal tibia with short- or medium-sized apophysis. Epigyne with sclerotized egigynal grooves which are spiral, with strongly sclerotized flanges (
<bibRefCitation author="Wesolowska W. &amp; Russell-Smith A." box="[197,618,447,473]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="553 - 619" refId="ref8594" refString="Wesolowska W. &amp; Russell-Smith A. 2011. Jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae) from southern Nigeria. Annales Zoologici 61: 553 - 619. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 000345411 x 603409" type="journal article" year="2011">Wesołowska &amp; Russell-Smith 2011</bibRefCitation>
), sometimes partially divided by arches associated with the genital openings. CD simple, spermathecae oval or bent (
<bibRefCitation author="Proszynski J." box="[773,975,483,510]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" refId="ref8380" refString="Proszynski J. 2016. Monograph of the Salticidae (Araneae) of the World 1995 - 2014. Chapter II: Global species database of Salticidae [online]. Available from http: // www. peckhamia. com / salticidae / index. html [accessed 1 Jul. 2016]." type="url" year="2016">Prószyński 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,342,549,575]" box="[189,342,549,575]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,549,575]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,549,575]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,1399,596,658]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
These are the first records of the genus for 
<collectingCountry box="[708,825,596,622]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[886,950,596,622]" name="India" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">India</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1902" box="[962,1060,597,622]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Brancus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[962,1060,597,622]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Brancus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was previously only known from Africa.
</paragraph>
